BT||HT|b|cs|1|cp|4|fp|3|at|^-{
Better Bridge with Bergen
    Responding to partner's splinter bid by Marty Bergen
    
BRIDGE BULLETIN June 20l2
}^-|CP||FP||cp|8|AT|

^b@2^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|Your partner has made a splinter bid. Did that improve your hand?|
PG| ***** 136 ***** |


AT|

The ideal holding in partner’s short suit is length and weakness. Once partner is void and can ruff, your low cards in the suit become winners—the more, the merrier. Having length in partner’s short suit means that you are likely to be short in the other suits and can ruff his losers. You’d also rather have your honors in partner’s longer suits where they’ll be more useful in building tricks.|
PG| ***** 137 ***** |


AT|

When your partner makes a splinter bid, your best holding is four or five cards along with very little (if any) high—card strength in partner’s short suit. Three low cards is also an excellent holding.|
PG| ***** 138 ***** |


AT|

Too many players believe that A-x-x is the perfect holding in partner’s short suit. Not true. You’d much prefer to have your Ace in partner’s longer suit.|
PG| ***** 139 ***** |


NT||
